      \field{labeldatesource}{}
      \true{uniqueprimaryauthor}
      \field{labelnamesource}{author}
      \field{labeltitlesource}{title}
      \field{abstract}{Extreme heat poses an increasing threat to human health due to global warming. Understanding how extreme weather events affect traffic crashes is crucial for assessing traffic risk factors and enhancing road safety. In this study, we utilized Hot Spot Analysis coupled with the Theil index and Spatial Durbin Model to investigate the characteristics of traffic crashes that occur on extremely hot days, using an 8-year panel dataset from the State of Florida, USA. The results revealed: 1) Crashes during extreme hot days (EHDs) show significant spatial clustering in regions typically characterized by colder climate zones, as temperature fluctuations from heat waves heighten the likelihood of traffic incidents. 2) Crashes during EHDs are more variable within regions experiencing high temperatures, where heat stress is compounded by high humidity or typical temperatures of tropical areas. 3) Crashes resulting from extreme heat are not isolated incidents but part of a chain reaction, highlighting the need for a systemic understanding of the hazards posed by extreme heat. Based on these insights, the study proposes targeted strategies to mitigate the risks associated with traffic crashes during EHDs. © 2024 Elsevier Ltd}
